 The staff of the Federal Trade Commission has concluded that the planned merger between the nation's largest bookseller and its largest book wholesaler violates antitrust law and has recommended that the full commission step in to block Barnes & Noble's $ 600 million acquisition of Ingram Book Group, a person involved in the deal said on Monday night.
In the past 12 months, the German conglomerate Bertelsmann AG completed its purchase of Random House, Barnes & Noble Inc. announced it would buy the world's largest wholesaler, the Ingram Book Group, and Bertelsmann and Barnes & Noble announced a joint investment in the on-line seller barnesandnoble.com.
 Facing intensifying competition, the nation's trade association for independent booksellers is creating its own national online store, Book Sense, to stave off fierce competition from Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com.
 Five months after Barnes & Noble Inc. rattled the book industry with the seismic announcement of its acquisition of the nation's largest wholesaler, Ingram Book Group, the proposed merger is undergoing intense federal scrutiny and is now being investigated by the California attorney general's office.
 When bookstore owner Michael Powell arrived at BookExpo America his schedule included leading a seminar on electronic publishing.
In their two-decades war against chain stores and, more recently, online booksellers, they have shared little beyond Barnes & Noble, Borders, Amazon, the price clubs and a will to survive.
